text:
‚ÄºÔ∏èsomething i‚Äôve never opened up about‚ÄºÔ∏è
.
extremely vulnerable post, but necessary. .
a few days ago, i got an email from medium about an article called ‚Äú#metoo will not survive unless we recognize toxic femininity.‚Äù usually i don‚Äôt open these emails, but this one i had to open. it was all about ‚Äúfeminism‚Äù destroying the culture. it is... we‚Äôve put in our mind that women must act a certain way or otherwise. sexual assault does not happen to just women believe it or not! it happens to men... to all you females out there denying it, it happens, women use men just as men use women. going off topic of the article, but just as it psychologically affects women, it does the same to men. so why am i even making this post & going off topic? i‚Äôm here to talk about the psychological effects of sexual assault. .
this article made me think back to a life event. easier said than done, i was sexually assaulted at the age of 14. something i have never opened up about. i was embarrassed & afraid. i was ‚Äúin love‚Äù with someone who hurt me physically & mentally. it affected my future relationships towards people (both friends and romantically), we won‚Äôt get into the high school ‚Äúcrushes‚Äù but that also took a toll on how i viewed myself.  i never finished my sophomore year of high school, no transcripts, nothing. after it happened, i felt like a piece of garbage to just throw away... for a long time. one thing that never changed though, i saw myself as strong & always wanted to be but was so weak mentally.  i never saw myself as i should have growing up, i missed a lot of ‚Äúthe best years‚Äù of my life... or did i? even up to just as little as 6 months ago, my anxiety was so bad that i would not let anyone unless i knew them very well touch me let alone near me. i lived in a bubble (a 4 foot personal space bubble). i lived in a mind where everyone was out to hurt me. i let it eat me alive for almost ten years. what changed? the view i had of myself. i finally saw myself as that strong, independent, woman that i am. lifting weights makes women manly, guess what? i‚Äôm loving every second of it. your opinion is irrelevant because i refused to be weak, both physically and mentally.

.

#repost @therestlessquill (@get_repost)
„Éª„Éª„Éª
here's a story about a sexual harasser, mohan polamar, who is also a yoga teacher. oh the access. 
this is the couple who runs the practice room @thepracticeroomdotin in wheeler road, bangalore. 
the women whom he harassed got together and created this comic.

when the women complained, the practice room put together a committee. this included the harasser's wife who also runs the place along with the harasser. 
there was flat out denial, gaslighting and aggression.  the women were told the complaint would be entertained only if there were more than 10 women who complained. when the women insisted, he was asked to take time off. but a month later he's back to teaching, having "reflected deeply." and then, the cleverest cut of all. the husband and wife duo have coopted this comic to circulate this among their classes claiming what a great illustration of how not to behave as a yoga teacher.

#metoo

text: when i asked @josemarines08 to take my photos a few months ago i asked him because i saw the images he had taken of his niece. they were simple yet gorgeous. i wanted to see some of me like that. i wanted to do a photo shoot with multiple outfits ...out in the middle of nowhere and just feel beautiful on the outside. oh my goodness how i truly struggled.... you can ask jose and his talented assistants.  i didn‚Äôt know how to stand, how to pose, i was afraid to smile or not to smile, and my own raised eyebrow gave me grief because of that ugly look it always makes me have. i‚Äôm not trying to be a model nor do i think i am. i almost lost my life 1/12/17 .... 24 mins of it is completely gone. i have no idea what happened while i was submerged in that canal. we shouldn‚Äôt wait for a near death experience to live we should take life by the reigns and grab hold of it every moment god enables us to breathe.  i‚Äôve been hearing all sorts of stories and the majority of the time i am fine, i pass it off and keep my head lifted high regardless of the pain that those words cause me internally. as chris cooper taught in church this morning i was reminded of love that kept me safe in that cold water, a love  that made me miss those two road signs completely, a love that is unconditional and eternal. he reminded me that even though i may not always understand love .....that god created me in love, with love, he reminded me to share his love, and that he will always, always love me.  now it‚Äôs time to love myself. you may not like me .... heck ya may hate me for some reason ... who knows. i tell ya what though .... even in the absence of self love ..... because of god i have always been able to shower others with love, compassion, sympathy, and i know deep in my soul that he sees that in me. these photos were taken and when i got them last night i immediately saw an opportunity to share my heart, my passion, my tears, my battle, my journey, my unspoken story, my success, my grief, my strength, my joy, and my soul. #iamhuman #iamgoodenough #iamworthy #iamloved #metoo #iamlivingpositive #journeyisaprocess

it happens to both men & women far more often than most realize.

text:
warning: sexual assault/harassment/rape

27th december 2015 was the day my life changed forever. my friend‚Äôs fianc√© came by to drop off a top i'd lent my friend. i invited him in, we chatted with a coffee, and he made a pass at me. pushing him away i walked away and he threw me onto my sofa and raped me.
he walked out my house as calmly as he walked in, and as soon as i heard his car leave my street, i called the police. aside from physical evidence, there were previous texts that proved i didn't plan to be alone with him (asking him to bring his daughter who was similar age to me) but he manipulated the situation to be on his own. all this, and the fact he was picked up by police whilst stuffing his clothes into the washing machine, saw him sentenced to 8 years in prison. this is my story, it is not over, and i'm working towards a happy ending. he will not break me. i am a survivor. #metoo #metoomovement #nomore

text: from left: fabolous, xxxtentacion, nas, russell simmons, and r. kelly.  throughout this past year of holding men in entertainment to task, the music industry has largely continued to overlook abuse allegations within its most popular genre, exhibiting a troubling lack of accountability. ben kothe / buzzfeed news; getty images.. october 2018 marks a year since hollywood juggernaut harvey weinstein was taken down by reports detailing decades of sexual harassment and abuse allegations against him. the titan‚Äôs fall catapulted tarana burke‚Äôs #metoo movement into a national phenomenon as women (and some men) felt empowered to call out their abusers. suddenly, actors, directors, writers, producers, and agents were forced to reckon with their past (and present) sexual misconduct. yet, throughout this past year of holding men in entertainment to task, the music industry has largely continued to turn a blind eye toward its most popular genre, hip-hop, exhibiting a lack of accountability where alleged abuse is concerned. the fact that many rap artists continue to thrive despite accusations of sexual and/or physical abuse is disconcerting. but it‚Äôs also less surprising considering the genre‚Äôs history of reflecting the intersections of american society, including the country‚Äôs complicated relationship between racism and rape. üìçread entire article at~ https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/sylviaobell/times-up-metoo-abusive-men-hip-hopüìçlink is also in my bio.. #rp @buzzfeednews

text:
‚Äúi was already thinking about this book, which i had decided to write in the months after the election, but had intended to report slowly, imagining that it would chronicle the steady evolution of women‚Äôs rage in the age of trump. but by the fall of 2017, as the wildfire of female fury was spreading, it had become clear that i needed to work swiftly, to capture this rebellion before its sharp, spiky contours got retroactively smoothed and flattened by time. and so i wrote these pages over the course of four months.‚Äù #rebeccatraister

it‚Äôs odd reading about a moment of transformative history while you‚Äôre still in it, unable to imagine what will happen next. it‚Äôs clear with every page that ‚Äògood and mad: the revolutionary power of women‚Äôs anger‚Äô will be assigned to students as an account of the trump era for decades to come, and traister is diligent in situating this moment in the long arc of women‚Äôs history. it is thoughtful and bloody and tries to push the new wave of feminist activism to be better even as it gets up and takes to the streets. how do we welcome newcomers to the fight for justice who don‚Äôt realize their awakening is not, ahem, original? how do we make sure white women don‚Äôt step on the toes of women of color who have been doing this work for decades? how do we harness the social capital and new energy of white women who truly do want to fight? how do we use our fury to demand a better world without burning out or turning on each other? traister doesn‚Äôt have all the answers, but she asks the right questions as she validates generations of anger. it‚Äôs a good reminder that fury is not a dirty word, it‚Äôs a powerful motivating force that is stigmatized because it threatens the world order. pick up a copy if you feel like your anger might eat you alive...and maybe give it to your male relatives this holiday season who keep talking about #metoo going too far. #bookish #bookstagram #bookclub #bookquotes #bookreview #feminism #feminist #anger #fury #rage #bluewave

you're crazy

just don't

text:
this series, at its core, is about sexual assault - but i am so sick of the level of disrespect towards women, immigrants, people of color, and the lgbtq community that radiates from the trump administration. our government is supposed to be ‚Äúfor the people,‚Äù but the only people they seem to consider people are rich, white, heterosexual men.

our spineless republican representatives continue to make excuses for trump‚Äôs increasingly abhorrent behavior. vote. them. out.

__________________________

each scene in this series was inspired by behaviors that made frequent appearances in the 22 accusations of sexual misconduct leveled against trump. the photos represent trump in his various public roles - pageant owner, golfer and campaigner, and president - but are not intended to convey one specific incident or point in time.

when donald trump was elected president in 2016, despite multiple allegations of sexual misconduct, i felt appalled and hopeless. just over a year later, when the #metoo movement was gaining traction, a huffpost/yougov poll showed that 66% of trump voters found the allegations against harvey weinstein credible, but that number dropped to 8% when asked about allegations against trump. now, another year later, credible accusations of sexual assault made against brett kavanaugh did very little to disrupt his confirmation to the supreme court. while we as citizens did not elect kavanaugh, trump‚Äôs dismissiveness of these accusations demonstrates the far-reaching effects of electing him as president. 
sexual assault should not be a partisan issue, and it makes me furious that it has become one. men who show such little respect for women have no place in government, regardless of their party affiliation. my hope is that these photographs cast these accusations in a new light and show the gravity of them in a way that a news story can‚Äôt. they are my plea to everyone who sees them to not only go out and vote, but to vote armed with knowledge, empathy, and purpose.

-
#beto is running on a mostly liberal agenda in #texas that is famously conservative and with little name recognition is raising money atypical for a statewide race. his opponent‚Äîa household name who ran for president in the last election cycle‚Äî has raised just over $33 million. o‚Äôrourke raised $38 million in the third quarter of this year alone, a record in a u.s. senate race.
-
even though o‚Äôrourke is raising so much more, he‚Äôs simultaneously refusing money from super pacs. sound familiar? bernie sanders, did the same thing.
-
beto isn‚Äôt just talking about texas specific things; he‚Äôs been quick to dive into national affairs. he went viral with his thoughts on #nfl players kneeling during the national anthem, on brett kavanaugh‚Äôs nomination, and he touts #immigration, #healthcare, and women‚Äôs health positions that are popular nationwide, but not so much in a conservative state.
-
it wasn‚Äôt long ago that a young, charming senator from illinois burst onto the national scene. his positions weren‚Äôt as popular in his state as they were to the country as a whole, but he was a fundraising machine who gained household notoriety harnessing the internet in a way candidates never had before. by the time he had his first u.s. senate seat, he was already one of the most popular democrats in the country.
-
he had a funny name too.
-
sound familiar? that‚Äôs because that plan worked out pretty well for #barackobama. the thing is, on top of all that charm, o‚Äôrourke has something even #obama didn‚Äôt have: he speaks spanish.

text:
the day of 2008 presidential election is  one i remember in stunning detail. huddled around my purple fluorescent-covered laptop, anticipation and the pure innocence of being a new voter hummed through me. the culmination of my newly declared major (sociology,) commitment to advocacy and whimsical idealistic imagination peaked when history was made on that night. proudly boasting my white t-shirt with bold blue letters tracing o b a m a '08, my feet carried me away from my computer screen and down the steps of my porch. i danced circles around my lawn, barefooted, screaming with joy. this. this was the beginning of representation for stigmatized individuals like me; the collective acknowledgment of invisible populations; the promise of equalizing change and empowerment for minority  members. as i twirled dreamily underneath the starlit evening, i marveled at the joy of seeing my own white faced, green-eyed reflection perfectly in my chosen representative. 
i think about that night often lately. mostly, i just want to cry, to mourn this memory like a beloved treasure...lost. what would happen if i wore that same t-shirt today? the truth is that i don't know that i would have the courage to leave my house wearing this shirt in 2018. my celebration of our former president's integrity, commitment to equality and character remain in tact. what before bloomed as a burgeoning desire to see oneself in the 'other,' though, has been crushed with a stampede to kill him. #vote ‚Ä¢

text:
this series, at its core, is about sexual assault - but i am so sick of the level of disrespect towards women, immigrants, people of color, and the lgbtq community that radiates from the trump administration. our government is supposed to be ‚Äúfor the people,‚Äù but the only people they seem to consider people are rich, white, heterosexual men.

our spineless republican representatives continue to make excuses for trump‚Äôs increasingly abhorrent behavior. vote. them. out.

__________________________

each scene in this series was inspired by behaviors that made frequent appearances in the 22 accusations of sexual misconduct leveled against trump. the photos represent trump in his various public roles - pageant owner, golfer and campaigner, and president - but are not intended to convey one specific incident or point in time.

when donald trump was elected president in 2016, despite multiple allegations of sexual misconduct, i felt appalled and hopeless. just over a year later, when the #metoo movement was gaining traction, a huffpost/yougov poll showed that 66% of trump voters found the allegations against harvey weinstein credible, but that number dropped to 8% when asked about allegations against trump. now, another year later, credible accusations of sexual assault made against brett kavanaugh did very little to disrupt his confirmation to the supreme court. while we as citizens did not elect kavanaugh, trump‚Äôs dismissiveness of these accusations demonstrates the far-reaching effects of electing him as president. 
sexual assault should not be a partisan issue, and it makes me furious that it has become one. men who show such little respect for women have no place in government, regardless of their party affiliation. my hope is that these photographs cast these accusations in a new light and show the gravity of them in a way that a news story can‚Äôt. they are my plea to everyone who sees them to not only go out and vote, but to vote armed with knowledge, empathy, and purpose.

text:
equal rights amendment - call to action

from the president‚Äôs desk: statement on action alert ‚Äì era amendment

today, there remains no equal rights amendment in the u.s., despite it being reintroduced to congress every session since not being ratified by the states in 1982. there are several states remaining that have not ratified the amendment. with the ratification of the equal rights amendment by the state of nevada in 2017 and by illinois as the 37th state in 2018, one more state is needed to ratify the equal rights amendment to achieve the initial 38 states for federal ratification as determined in 1982. if one more state ratifies the era, the ratification process will move into the courts for determination regarding the constitutionality of the original deadline that was applied to the equal rights amendment.

in the wake of women-led movements like the women‚Äôs march and #metoo, era activists have found renewed energy and current efforts to ratify the era are active in north carolina, tennessee, and florida.
but we can change this! it is important that americans understand the reality of gender inequality; that men and women are not guaranteed equal rights by law yet. i believe everyone was born with equal rights and are entitled to them as citizens of this great nation of ours. the amendment reads:

section 1. equality of rights under the law shall not be denied or abridged by the united states or by a state on account of sex.

section 2. the congress shall have the power to enforce, by appropriate legislation, the provisions of this article. 
section 3. this amendment shall take effect two years after the date of ratification.

ncbw‚Äôs call to action is to urge chapters to tell their members and encourage family, friends, and community to contact their congressional representatives by email, phone, or an in-person visit to their office as quickly as possible to support the equal rights amendment and ask them to help push for its ratification ‚Äì it is a crucial piece of legislation!

can i count on you?

in the spirit of impactful advocacy,
 virginia w. harris, national president
#ncbwinc #ncbwoc #equalrightsamendment #calltoaction #100blackwomenoc #oc

text:
india is currently undergoing its own #metoo movement.

at last weeks jio mami mumbai film festival, the biggest film festival in india, the #metoo movement made giant leaps. after gathering speed for two weeks before the festival, two features and three shorts were cancelled after allegations arose against people involved in them.

although the festival director anupama chopra (pictured) apologised for disappointing audiences, she hoped that people would understand that they had 'to stand with the women who have raised their voices'. in the place of the cut films and shorts, female-driven films highlighting diversity and strength in indian cinema were shown.

#metoo #indiametoo #jiomamimumbaifilmfestival #feminism #feminist #women #strongwomen #anupamachopra #abouttimes

üëè new episode sponsored by @foundcoffeela: @aapiwomenlead: #imready üëè ‚Äúthe #imready movement aims to strengthen the progressive political and social platforms of asian and pacific islander communities in the us through the leadership of self-identified aapi women and girls.  our goal is to challenge and help end the intersections of violence against and within our communities. we do this work in solidarity with other communities of color.
.
the #imready movement raises visibility around self-identified aapi women and our experiences with #metoo, racial discrimination, war, immigration, and more. it also celebrates the leadership and power of aapi women in education, business, technology, and politics. at the conferences, we bring together aapi women leaders and our supporters to learn from one another, tell our stories, and to highlight our diverse leadership stories.
.
we invite you to join us to better understand the complex asian and pacific islander diasporas, histories, and experiences. we invite you to come honor the stories and leadership of our communities.
.
we are bringing together some of the most brilliant people to explore what it means to be a self-identified aapi woman in the united states. we know you are one of them.‚Äù
.
connie wun, ph.d., is co-founder of aapi women lead, a non-profit organization that helps to support the progressive social and political platforms of asian and pacific islander communities in the u.s through the leadership of self-identified women and girls.

text:
i was just messaged by a swing dancer that back in 2010, when she was a minor, i made inappropriate remarks about her physicality, like saying she was hot. i was 100% part of the problem. i am very sorry to her and anyone else i hurt that way. 
within the last year, it was pointed out to me that i made sexual comments on a friend's photos that were uncalled for and i realized that was true so i made an effort to stop.

this is not some "look how far i've come" post. it's a "i fuck up and do harmful stuff" post. i'm not going to stop trying to share things about feminism and empowering women. i'm not going to stop trying to be better. but i've definitely done shitty things in my past. don't let people get away with it because they seem nice or whatever. we have to work at it and sometimes we'll never make things right, but that's no reason for us not to do the work.

i've apologized in the dm to the woman who was so brave as to let me know and i'm going to stay away from her as she requested. if i've hurt you, too, you are also welcome to let me know. i am very sorry for the harm i've caused.

text:
a little bit of a throwback.. üí´
.
.
.
.
as most of you know i used to model a lot, all the time, sometimes numerous shoots a day.. but something happened to me almost two years ago that completely burst my bubble. other then promotional work i virtually stopped modelling all together, only shooting every 6 months or so with photographers i know and really trust.. my dream of combining my career in modelling and my nutrition degree was put on hold essentially whilst i worked through some things. some things that hopefully one day i'll be able to revisit in order to let people know about the injustice i went through even so recently.. it is sad when one has to paint a dark picture of another in order to paint a "better" picture of themselves.

but my happy sunday post this evening is that i am working on becoming accredited as a nutritionist (to be able to practice and have patients), i'm back cooking healthy food for loved ones and going to the gym. i'm warning my favourite photographers i will be bothering you soon!! i'm finally in a good place and my future, i'm ready for you.. üçáüîÆüíú and you know what they say.. hell hath no fury like a woman scorned ü§£üòâüòö #fitness #nutrition #model #future #goodvibes #photoshoot #weekend #newweek #newstart #metoo #metoomovement #promogirl #happy #happyatlast #everythinghappensforareason

text:
"when did loving yourself become so rare it‚Äôs revolutionary to do so‚Äù

this year i have definitely become more aware of how people view themselves and how i view myself. loving yourself is probably one of the most important things in today‚Äôs society thanks to the pressures we face due to social media and beauty expectations. i am lucky that i have grown up in a loving family where my parents would tell me and my brother off for ever using the word ‚Äúugly‚Äù to describe our or someone else‚Äôs appearance. they taught me that no one is ugly and as i have grown older i see that everyone is beautiful in their own and unique way.

although i have gained confidence in myself this year it is still a work in progress. i have always liked certain things about myself such as my eyes, hair and my friendly personality, however there are things i am still learning to love; my pale skin, my chubby cheeks, the gap between my teeth  and ability to overthink every situation. as time progresses i found myself loving more and more of myself.

accept that there will be days where you don‚Äôt look or feel your best for everyone has bad days. however make sure you acknowledge the times where you feel confident and good about yourself, when wearing your favourite outfit or if your makeup turned out good you look at yourself in the mirror and tell yourself ‚Äúdamn! i look good today‚Äù. for some finding one thing to love about yourself can be difficult, you may look in the mirror and think ‚Äúi don‚Äôt like anything about myself‚Äù if this is you i challenge you to start by finding just one thing that you like about yourself it can be appearance or personality or even a talent you have and slowly add more things to this list.

be patient with yourself as being confident and loving yourself doesn‚Äôt happen overnight and remember you‚Äôre all beautiful in your own unique way.

text:
it's our pleasure to introduce alisha gill.

alisha gill has always been fascinated by science and after seeing the ocean for the first time as a child, she knew she wanted to become a marine biologist. alisha studied biology at montana sate university where she received her b.sc. in 2015. in 2016 she was accepted into a master's program at the university of guam marine laboratory. 
alisha was just awarded her m.sc. in biology this summer. her research was on the spawning behaviors of the bird wrasse (a tropical fish species). she compared the spawning success of different males within a spawning aggregation and their reactions to egg predators. living on a tiny tropical island surrounded by ocean fueled her passion for life underwater and made her want to share her excitement with others. alisha became enthusiastic about science communication and strives to make science available to those without a background in it. in her free time you can find alisha knitting, skiing, scuba diving, or making music.

we welcome you to the addictive brain community and we look forward to reading your contributions.

text:
#metoo the scariest hashtag which is being used very commonly these days. i don't know for whom is it more scary, for the victim or for the culprit? because either of them never went through the experience which they actually deserve after coming out or being exposed.  no matter from where you belong or in which industry or career or phase of life you're in right now, you've all the right to speak up about it because harassment is unacceptable. i live in a society where people make fun of such things before taking them seriously. speaking up about sexual assault or harassment isn't as easy as we suppose to think. sometimes the victim have to go through a lot of questions but people never think that the person who's being alleged have to be questioned too. 
i have seen a lot of men reacting aggressively towards this topic. they think that it's some kind of disgrace to their gender but in reality such incidents can happen to anyone, there's no gender limitation in this crime. 
i have witnessed that most of the people on social media believe that these allegations are nothing more than a hoax. i want to say one thing to them coming out and speaking up may look easy but expressing what you've been through in front of everyone is the most courageous yet the most painful moment for the victim. just take a moment and imagine the worst memory of your life and then you can feel how these people feel when they speak about their worst nightmare. speaking up on social media is like telling the whole world about your pain. 
let me remind you something, harassment can happen to anyone and anywhere. all you have to do is to listen the person, let them feel you're with them and you believe them, no matter if the harasser is a complete stranger and you probably will never see him or her again but it's your duty to make the victim feel powerful. tell the victim that you can change the situation and control it too. let them know about little self defense tricks. make them aware about that your little actions can bring extreme changes. 
#metoo #harassment #respectconsent #respectno #bloggerlife #bloggernetwork #bloggerlifestyle #blogs #bloggerlifestyle #bloggers #speaking #speakthr

text:
when i tell people what i am going to school for and my future job title i get a variety of responses. mostly "oh man you must have great sex!" or "i could definitely use your help." but the one that makes me most nervous is "what does that do, what problems are there within sex and sexuality?" üò≤

the fact that people don't know how many issues we are dealing with as a society and individually when it comes to sex. for example the #metoo movement is a huge symptom of our sex education. people usually have harmful sexual issues that are subconscious that effects different parts of your life.  take the time to do a self audit regarding your views and relationship with sex and your sexuality. it requires the same attention any mental health topic does.

btw got to check out the wilmington riverfront and we love it!! so beautiful and some great bars and shops.

text:
i learned something new today. üí´
.
many youth have reached out to me sharing how my coming out story in yoga journal inspired them. üôåüèº
.
my heart skips a beat. i sometimes cry...hard...with gratitude that i was in this era of #metoo, i am exquisitely sensitive to the need for people to help protect other people, and little scares me more than young children and youth. i can barely imagine the internal struggles parents face when young children want to engage on social media. i would be terrified for my kid. üßíüèº .
when youth reach out to me on social media, i go out of my way to tell them that the internet is a big place. that they should never feel pressure to do anything they would be shy to tell their parents about. that there are real dangers online. and...that if they are ever concerned about someone or shy to talk to their parents, they can come to me. i am happy to hear and help. üë©‚Äçüë¶
.
@lindseyelmore shared a post and used the words, ‚Äòsafe adult.‚Äô this is the first time i‚Äôve heard this phrase and can feel its deep need.
.
youth that follow this page. i love you. you can always come here if someone makes you uncomfortable in a way that you are scared to tell your parents. you can come here if your parents don‚Äôt love you or ignore you. if you did something or if something happened to you that you are ashamed of, wish didn‚Äôt happen, or made you feel not right, i am here for you. if no one else has told you today, i love you. you have safe space. ‚òÆÔ∏è
.
be safe out there children and youth. you are precious beyond measure. no one has the right to make you do anything you don‚Äôt want to do. no one should invite you to meet them if you can‚Äôt tell your parents. no one can touch you in ways that you don‚Äôt like. no one. üôÖüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
speak up. safe adults are listening. üëÇüèª
.
#safeadult

text:
the domestic violence and sexual assault council of greater miami dvsac second annual summit. this year we focused on domestic violence lethality and prevention.
amazing event ! outstanding panelists who provided the audience with a very relevant information guiding us in understanding the magnitude of this social issue in miami dade. 
i‚Äôm highly appreciative with the our keynote speaker the honorable judge carroll kelly who delivered a powerful message. great gratitude with miami dade county 11th court circuit, domestic violence division, office of the state attorney katherine fernandez rundle, florida health department for their support and participation. as every year this event couldn‚Äôt be possible without the support of the city of miami police department, miami dadepolice department, city of miami gardens police department,  city of hialeah police department, coral gables police department nd city of miami beach police department. especial gratitude with albizu university for hosting our event, with florida international, university of miami school of law, florida national university and the power house and to miami dade college. highly appreciative with the bar association dade legal aid and vida legal assistance.  to our supporters thank you once again the women funds of miami, nicole alvarez law pa, and quayum and garcia pa. 
@florida.health @healthy_fla @miamidadehaab @advocacymdc @funcionartecorp @isadoracuba @unitednations @survivorspathwayorganization @miamibeachpd @miamisup @miamidadepd @mpdpolice @cityofcoralgables @cityofmiamigardens @cityofmiami @cityofdoral @cityofhialeah @hialeahgardenspd @sao4florida @dadelegalaidpsb @floridanationaluniversity @fiuinstagram @univmiami @albizumia @karamat_qayum @nalvarezesq @womensfundmiami #survivorspathway #metoo #humanrights #domesticviolence #lgbt #nomore

text:
the domestic violence and sexual assault council of greater miami dvsac second annual summit. this year we focused on domestic violence lethality and prevention.
amazing event ! outstanding panelists who provided the audience with a very relevant information guiding us in understanding the magnitude of this social issue in miami dade. 
i‚Äôm highly appreciative with the our keynote speaker the honorable judge carroll kelly who delivered a powerful message. great gratitude with miami dade county 11th court circuit, domestic violence division, office of the state attorney katherine fernandez rundle, florida health department for their support and participation. as every year this event couldn‚Äôt be possible without the support of the city of miami police department, miami dadepolice department, city of miami gardens police department,  city of hialeah police department, coral gables police department nd city of miami beach police department. especial gratitude with albizu university for hosting our event, with florida international, university of miami school of law, florida national university and the power house and to miami dade college. highly appreciative with the bar association dade legal aid and vida legal assistance.  to our supporters thank you once again the women funds of miami, nicole alvarez law pa, and quayum and garcia pa. 
@florida.health @healthy_fla @miamidadehaab @advocacymdc @funcionartecorp @isadoracuba @unitednations @survivorspathwayorganization @miamibeachpd @miamisup @miamidadepd @mpdpolice @cityofcoralgables @cityofmiamigardens @cityofmiami @cityofdoral @cityofhialeah @hialeahgardenspd @sao4florida @dadelegalaidpsb @floridanationaluniversity @fiuinstagram @univmiami @albizumia @karamat_qayum @nalvarezesq @womensfundmiami #survivorspathway #metoo #humanrights #domesticviolence #lgbt #nomore

text:
the domestic violence and sexual assault council of greater miami dvsac second annual summit. this year we focused on domestic violence lethality and prevention.
amazing event ! outstanding panelists who provided the audience with a very relevant information guiding us in understanding the magnitude of this social issue in miami dade. 
i‚Äôm highly appreciative with the our keynote speaker the honorable judge carroll kelly who delivered a powerful message. great gratitude with miami dade county 11th court circuit, domestic violence division, office of the state attorney katherine fernandez rundle, florida health department for their support and participation. as every year this event couldn‚Äôt be possible without the support of the city of miami police department, miami dadepolice department, city of miami gardens police department,  city of hialeah police department, coral gables police department nd city of miami beach police department. especial gratitude with albizu university for hosting our event, with florida international, university of miami school of law, florida national university and the power house and to miami dade college. highly appreciative with the bar association dade legal aid and vida legal assistance.  to our supporters thank you once again the women funds of miami, nicole alvarez law pa, and quayum and garcia pa. 
@florida.health @healthy_fla @miamidadehaab @advocacymdc @funcionartecorp @isadoracuba @unitednations @survivorspathwayorganization @miamibeachpd @miamisup @miamidadepd @mpdpolice @cityofcoralgables @cityofmiamigardens @cityofmiami @cityofdoral @cityofhialeah @hialeahgardenspd @sao4florida @dadelegalaidpsb @floridanationaluniversity @fiuinstagram @univmiami @albizumia @karamat_qayum @nalvarezesq @womensfundmiami #survivorspathway #metoo #humanrights #domesticviolence #lgbt #nomore

these words were spoken by an american president almost 80 years ago ....when did so many of the american people forget what it really means to be american ... (nevermind just being a decent person , christian or otherwise .... )

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text: growing up i remember so clearly when my dad would complain about the state of the world. my mom called it his ‚Äòthe world is going to hell in a handbasket‚Äô kick. i was an optimistic kid, and i remember thinking that the world was never going to get any better or brighter by virtue of our harping on the negative. now that i‚Äôm a grown up myself reading headlines about shootings in synagogues and yoga studios and menacing reports on the future of climate change, oh man do i get it. i‚Äôm noticing how easy it is to slide into fear and frustration; how hard it is to resist the temptation to tell the story that the world is tumbling into a space beyond repair. but i‚Äôm gonna challenge myself to keep consciously choosing to believe that love is still the strongest force on the planet. i‚Äôm holding out hope that by honestly acknowledging the negative but choosing to headline the positive, i‚Äôm creating space for hope and change. even the darkest moments have their silver lining. may we all have the opportunity to find new ways to believe in the innate goodness of humanity and love harder-the world needs it now more than ever. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ú®what beliefs about the world are you holding most tightly to today? #love #hope #bethechange #strength #optimism #theworldisyours #metoo #positivity #bravery#consciousness #spiritualawakening #breathe #theworldisyours #globalwarming #empowerment #liveyourbestlife

text:
you know what‚Äôs required before anyone, including obstetrical care providers, performs any procedure?
‚Ä¢
consent.
‚Ä¢
you know what‚Äôs often not given? respect for the person that‚Äôs laying on that examination table. there is exactly zero consideration for their struggle, their story, their trauma.
‚Ä¢
consent is absent in obstetrical care, and it‚Äôs absurd.
‚Ä¢
it is not difficult to enter a room, introduce yourself, explain a procedure (cervical exam, for example), and then ask if they are okay with you touching them before you begin.
‚Ä¢
for many people, they are told their entire lives that it‚Äôs sacred space. space that is only for them or the person they trust and love. once you‚Äôre pregnant, the idea of the sacred space is null and void. everyone wants to put their hands in your vagina and nobody cares if you don‚Äôt want them to.
‚Ä¢
how did we get to this place? the place where care providers take it upon themselves to decide what is and is not appropriate and allowed.
‚Ä¢
if you‚Äôre uncomfortable with anything, you get to say no. we can‚Äôt perpetuate rape culture right here in a space that we‚Äôre supposed to trust and feel safe in. consent is not a hard concept, and it should be applied in both the medical model of care and the midwifery model of care.

text:
as i sat on the beach this week meditating & planning, i was overwhelmed with gratitude that i could even be partaking in such beauty. the moments that followed the sun fully setting below the horizon were indeed magical.  the deep reds and pinks, oranges bouncing off the ethereal clouds gave a magnificent contrast against the vivid blue sky.  i looked down to write only to be delighted in the burst of bright light reflecting off the clouds above. this was a sunset like non other. it was glorious to behold. it is difficult to fully explain but if you were there, you knew. and sometimes just being present is enough.
üì∏: me!!

text:
my friends! long time no see. my reappearance has been overdue by the obligations of everyday life but i'm back on track and eager to tell you stories of nomad life:‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
"horses have four legs though they often fall." this is a nigerian proverb to just simply say that fear to failure should not be a reason for anyone to fail to chase their dreams. like many, i've been struggling with fear, anxiety and equating of my self worth with performance for a good 10 years of my life. about a year ago i finally decided to do something about it by wrestling these emotions head-on! "what's the worst that could happen?" "what if life should end today, is it worth all this hassle?" these questions were enough to give some perspective and i thank god for allowing me to hit rock bottom in order to only be able to look up, get up and now fearlessly chasing those dreamsüèÉüèæ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è. only by his grace!‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
how do you wrestle your fearsüí™üèæ?‚†Ä

text:
this is challenging. and my heart breaks for these individuals, families, and the local and global community of yogis and yoginis.
in a yoga/spiritual/awareness practice we create the conditions and container for alignment and ahimsa/peace to arise,  unfold,  and take hold into our lives and the world around us.  political and community leaders do the same.

one aspect of spirituality is to stay in a neutral field of awareness to inspire and uplift others in a positive way.  another aspect is to draw your sword (whatever that means to you) and go to battle ( ask ajuna in the bhagavad - gita)

we are  at a collective turning point where it is no longer enough to keep the practice of yoga  on the mat, we need to bring it to the world through raised awareness and action. to the world of business, politics, activism, art, our bodies, the earth, climate change,  and every other aspect of the 3d ( we are not here to negate the 3d, we are here to infuse it with a higher light and vibration.  ask gaia)
to not step up in full active warrior pose at this time is to stay stuck, complacent,  and miss the opportunity for yoga and other spiritual/awareness practices to become more relevant in the world, and to  perhaps fulfill their higher calling in this present age.

there are a 1000 ways to co-create the conditions of peace , justice,  and balance on the planet. voting is one of them . #vote

text:
honoring those lost last week, and the community that grieves them. it is scary to shine your light into the darkness, to speak out against injustice, to rise up when your are afraid and hurting. but you can, and you must, to the best of your ability. we all have times for quiet healing, and we all have reservations about being really truly seen. i cannot promise you won‚Äôt lose relationships, followers, or clients for it. you probably will. but you will also gain more like-minded community than you knew existed. .
.
a few years ago i made a conscious decision to be seen. i started to speak directly to those who catcalled me, to speak up when i saw others being harrassed, to shine a light on injustice and oppression when i recognize it (i‚Äôm still learning and unraveling my own complicity in this). i was fairly sheltered, privileged, and naive growing up, and all this was really uncomfortable. i did not know #metoo would follow. i was also one of those people who was really blind-sided by the 2016 election results, even if this should have been foreseeable. i did not realize, when i started to be more visible, what that would mean in these times. i just knew i had to speak out. it has been imperfect, and i know i have a lot more to learn. but i am glad to be holding out my latern, even if my arm shakes as i do so. sending you strength, healing, and courage on this sunday. i am proud of you, pittsburgh.
.
.

text: cutting hair, editing a photo differently, none of these things are just about an aesthetic. they're about creating a feeling. for me, specifically, a feeling i had 8 years ago of being unburdened and free. a feeling that was robbed from me when i crossed paths with someone who took advantage of my innocence. when i couldn't face myself in the mirror and i let my hair grow long like an extra layer of protection. each morning we wake up and we're reborn, we're not the same person we were the day before or week before or decade before. or at least we don't have to be. we wake up with the chance to be real and vulnerable with those who love and support us, with the opportunity to recreate, and with the gift of language so that we can express these changes to the people in our lives, who can either join us on our journey or, if their path is different, we can collaborate on how each of our own unique paths can continue to cross. i know i'm behind with this share, but i can only express myself in my own timing. when i was 17 i attended an ayahuasca ceremony in peru. three hours into it i still didn't feel a thing while the rest of the journeyers were deep into the medicine, and then alone in my hotel room, around 3 in the morning, i began to have one of the most transformative experiences of my life. i honor my process, i begin to peel away at painful layers from the past, and i stand in sisterhood with all of you who feel the stinging of untended wounds. #metoo
name: Hadas Knox ‚Üü Rooted Living

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
words cannot describe how fortunate i feel to live in a state that makes voting so easy. colorado offers mail-in ballots, 24-hour drop-off locations, early voting, and same day voter registration.

many of us are privileged to not be affected by the rampant practices of voter suppression that plague this country. we are privileged to have available time and resources that make it easy to turn in our ballots. shit- we are privileged to live in a country where we can even vote at all.

numerous people do not have this privilege. it saddens me to think that there are folks out there who would give anything to vote, but face barriers to doing so. it breaks my heart even more so that people who face no obstacles simply choose not to vote.

midterm elections are important and your vote makes a difference. these ballot measures directly affect your local community. the candidates chosen will determine who controls the house and senate. we determine whether or not the current administration goes unchecked. 
you have 2 1/2 more days. check out gettothepolls.com to find an early voting site or election day site near you.

‚Ä¢ vox by christina dalcher ‚Äò a novel ripe for the era of #metoo.‚Äô ‚Ä¢ genre dystopian fiction ‚Ä¢ 327 pages ‚Ä¢ 4/5 rating .
.
.
think about waking up one morning and finding you don't have a voice in anything. think about speaking only 100 words a day because you are a woman whereas the men can speak as much as they want to. .
.
‚Äòthe pure religious movement‚Äô was started and all females (as young as 5 year old kids) were fitted with a word counting ‚Äòbracelet‚Äô with a daily word limit of 100 and severe consequences followed if they crossed that threshold. .
.
.
the premise of the book from the blurb got to me. and dang that is one terrifying reality i‚Äôm sure nobody would want and a scary nagging feeling i got as a woman was that what if it does get true? it‚Äôs about the extent to which men will go to silence women in order to get them ‚Äòdomesticated‚Äô and withhold patriarchy. not just that, it‚Äôs about us as a society who do nothing to prevent such laws from being enforced, the bystanders who refuse to take a stand for a better world, who choose to ignore because the cause doesn‚Äôt disturb their comforts. the book is shocking, terrifying, and mind blowing at the same time. .
.
.
i literally felt the tension and my heart kept pounding with every single advancement in the story, even though it‚Äôs fictional i know the catastrophic consequences of this movement. and as a woman it‚Äôs scary to digest but it‚Äôs not too far fetched or impossible because of the world we live in. men trying to silence women is not something we haven‚Äôt heard of and that‚Äôs why it‚Äôs a commendable debut even though there are loopholes we still need to read such books which is why i recommend this book. one must know and realise what all is capable of happening if we stay ignorant and silent towards what‚Äôs already happening! .
.

text:
when people ask us about this project, we‚Äôre very open about its origination in the #metoo movement. in late 2017, we saw the power and freedom these simple words gave women to express the experiences they‚Äôd suppressed for so long. we jumped in as people around us started engaging in conversations about consent and change.
.
as we dug in further, we realized that the problems with our culture around sex don‚Äôt just boil down to a few bad actors. our lack of education, resources, conversation, and support is also a huge contributing issue. when we don‚Äôt talk about sex and pleasure, but instead bury them under shame, those areas of our overall health and wellbeing become toxic environments that breed anger, fear, resentment, suppression, and pain. sound familiar?
.
we‚Äôre certainly not excusing people who abuse their power. we absolutely believe that everyone should take responsibility for their actions. and, as we look forward to future generations, we believe it‚Äôs impossible to create lasting change without shifting the way we educate, communicate, and support. frankly, where we stand today is archaic.
.
truly solving these problems will require cross collaboration between governments, workplaces, researchers, activists, and so many more groups of people. and every step we take to open up the conversation around sex, pleasure, and consent makes a difference. that‚Äôs why we‚Äôre creating this journal ‚Äî and why we make it a point to ask about and listen openly to people‚Äôs experiences, particularly the ones they haven‚Äôt had a space to share before. releasing these stories into a safe space is an important step to eliminating shame and finding freedom.
.
if you‚Äôre standing up, we‚Äôre standing with you. what stories do you want to tell?
.
üì∑ by @ronyhernandes

text: hey 18-34 year olds! i hear only 26% of you plan to vote next week. look, i know you're busy. i know it's inconvenient. i know it might feel like one vote doesn't matter. but you need to do it anyways. you might think it's unimportant; you might think the outcome won't affect you. and you know what, that might be true if you are a wealthy, white, "christian," cis-gendered, straight male. but for those of us who are sexual or racial minorities, or who pray to a different god, or do not have the resources to pay for basic needs like shelter, healthcare, and education -- our lives are at risk. if you agree that black lives do matter, that kids should be able to go to school without fearing a massacre, that science is real, that women have a right to make choices about their own bodies, that we all deserve the freedom to love who we love and express our true identities -- you need to get your ass to a polling place on tuesday. if you need a ride, ask for help! if you need time off from work to vote, ask for help! if you are confused about how to vote, ask for help! but do not sit there and do nothing. you do matter and so does your vote.

text:
repair is thrilled to welcome jerrika hinton @hellojerrika as a storyteller in two weeks at "clarity: a storytelling event". get more information about clarity, and our 2018-2019 series, "transformation: lectures, conversations and storytelling about healing and social action", at: repairconnect.org/events "clarity" is on saturday, 11/17 from 2-4pm at mercado la paloma, 3655 s. grand ave, in los angeles @mercadolapaloma. free & open to the public. co-sponsored by a new way of life reentry project @anewwayoflifela & ralph j. bunche center for african-american studies at ucla @bunchecenter about jerrika: born and raised in dallas, texas, jerrika hinton has been performing since the age of 4. she studied both playwriting and directing at the meadows school of arts at southern methodist university and was awarded their rosenfeld award for playwriting. hinton is most known for her five seasons of #blackgirlmagic on grey's anatomy. most recently, she appeared on the hbo series, here & now. when not working, hinton loves exploring photography, lock-picking, and forgetting to return texts. one day she will live on a farm at the edge of the world.

#freeevents #losangeles #clarity #transformation #metoo #believesurvivors #yesallwomen #healing #socialchange #socialaction #greysanatomy #hereandnow #hbo #socialjustice #blackwomen #womenofcolor #storytelling #picoftheday #courage #integrity #playwriting #strength #womenleaders @blackfeminism #community

text:
@jerrysaltz @robertasmithnyt we would love your post #metoo thoughts on this topic. especially you, jerry, as a man, your opinion, whatever that may be, is important, and so far has been missing from an art critic with such a large platform. (correct me if i‚Äôm wrong.) peter schjeldahl your opinion has been made clear after your thoughts on balthus: ‚Äúnow i find myself at the other pole of my ambivalence, affirming the work‚Äôs aesthetic excellence and historical importance, for what that‚Äôs worth, in an argument about the proper physical disposition and critical framing of ‚Äúth√©r√®se dreaming.‚Äù at present, the met is standing by its commitment to display the painting. i concur, while also respecting the sensitivity of the petitioners. i doubt that we have heard the last of the controversy. any decisive resolution, one way or another, can be neither moral nor aesthetic, only political.‚Äù (peter @realisim  i‚Äôd love your critique on the balthus polaroids that @gagosian sells for $20,000 each) your antiquated views post #metoo will hopefully put you on the wrong side of art criticism in decades to come, and i hope that‚Äôs what you‚Äôre remembered for in one hundred years. perhaps i‚Äôm wrong though. 
obviously censorship is out of the question, educating is the answer, not withholding the truth. we are slowly moving towards belief systems that are no longer binary. this applies to art criticism too.

aesthetics can still be critiqued while presenting the truth about artists, and using the excuse that we‚Äôd have to put an asterisk next to most artist‚Äôs work in museums is ‚Äútoo much‚Äù isn‚Äôt an option, it‚Äôs lazy.

many people learn about picasso and other artists solely through museums. last night i enacted an unsanctioned performance/call to action at @metmuseum to separate the art from the artist, using the words of my hero @hannah_gadsby a comedian and art historian who so articulately spoke about this topic on her netflix comedy special nanette. (she wasn‚Äôt involved in this so i don‚Äôt want to implicate her)
‚Äúthe history of western art is just the history of men painting women like they‚Äôre flesh vases for their dick flowers.‚Äù - @hannah_gadsby @roxanegay74

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text: sound resides tremendous power for healing. it opens hearts to connect with the essence of who you are in a safe and sacred way. i integrate #soundhealing with my client sessions because i believe that it truly does helps them connect to a part of themselves they never thought possible. from my own experience it has helped soothe the symptoms that i experience with #cptsd and if i can help others feel a moment of peace then i have my done my part to be of service. friday night i had the opportunity to be of service at swiha's 1st gifts & graces at its new location. connecting with so many beautiful new friends made my heart sing. many shared that they had cried and for the moment that we shared together they experienced something that they hadn't felt in such a long time.

i had the honor of performing at @vb_justiceinitiative‚Äôs ‚Äòcelebrate justice‚Äô fundraiser bringing awareness to human trafficking and raising money for the cause.  the event, while beautiful, shed light on the ugliness of human trafficking and what we as a community can do to stop it.  the keynote speaker was ms. barbara amaya, a survivor, author and activist, who stands proof as to why this cause is so important.  after running away from a toxic and abusive home at the age of 12, she was picked up by a trafficker more than twice her age and made to live ‚Äúthe life‚Äù for the next decade.  the things she described‚Äî i wish upon no one, let alone a child. yet, it‚Äôs happening right under our noses every day.  she has made it her mission to turn her pain into purpose, operating under her motto: ‚Äúno about us, without us‚Äù, meaning... no matter how or where or what cause you advocate for, never forget to include the voices of those who actually fought to survive it.- neisha h.
‚Ä¢
for more info on how you can stop human trafficking, please visit www.vbji.org and/or your local human trafficking advocacy agency.

text:
@younique_corporate  is so generous and giving. i can honestly say that i have never worked for a more caring company! i swear i still have days that i can't believe that i actually get paid to do things like this.

i recently attended the #empoweryounc and it was an experience i will always cherish, as all younique experiences are. yes... they gave out a lot of amazing goodies... but that isn't what truly makes me love this company and what i do.

while i'm not quite ready to share my story publicly, being able to talk one on one with someone (in all the shaking hands and nerves of actually approaching him i kind of forgot his name) that helps with the @youniquefoundation and tell him what #thehavenretreat meant to me and how much it changed my life... heck saved my mental health and helped me get to a place where i know i am worthy of help and that no matter what my inner voice says i am making progress... i am a survivor! y'all, i can't even begin to tell you what it meant to me. not only was i able to go to the convention center and be surrounded, and of course bumped into, by 800+ strangers... i approached and talked with a man (alone!) i had never met before... something that would have most likely sent me into a panic attack before the retreat.

i wish that i could find a way to thank each and every person involved with this foundation, because what they do is priceless! what they do is make it possible for women like me to change our mindset... to go from thinking of ourselves as victims to survivors. we learn to #reclaimhope and believe in ourselves.

#uplift #empower #validate #youniquepresenter  #metoo #survivor #somebodyshoulddosomething #iamthatsomeone #nomore1in4

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
glow moment- chillin‚Äô headed to watch the @rza do a live scoring of the 1978 kungfu classic ‚Äúthe 36th chamber of shaolin‚Äù- which was sensational... our boy @mattmcgorry did an excellent job moderating a conversation with our sister @taranajaneen about #metoo and where we are 1 year later. tarana said ‚Äúthere is only one man i would sit in conversation with- and it‚Äôs matt‚Äù. we love men are doing the work and who who really get it! 
_
the last time i got to see my dear @opalayo was last week, when she skyped into our level 2 doula immersion weekend and spoke to my doula daughters about movement building, social justice and her human rights work as co-founder of black lives matter @blklivesmatter and executive director at baji (black alliance for just immigration). stay tuned for more from the two of us in 2019. 
_

in 1993, sarah lucas and tracey emin collaborated on ‚Äúthe shop‚Äù‚Äîliterally, a store they started together in #london for fun. there, they began selling #tshirts, badges, and other items with absurd and outrageous phrases such as "#completearsehole‚Äù. the tongue-in-cheek shirts encapsulated the cultural moment, while also offering up a comedic critique of sexism and classism. the shop eventually turned into a hangout for #artists, but also was a space for emin and lucas to simply cut loose, make work, and sell #art on their own terms. 
it is evident how influential sarah‚Äôs work has been for so many younger artists addressing crucial debates about #gender and power, the body, and the fluidity of identity. her works also have particular resonance in this current moment of cultural reckoning, with widespread revelations about pervasive misconduct coming to light in movements such as #metoo. her works get right to the core of many of the issues that have long affected society, many of which are coming to light today.

text:
here's a story about a sexual harasser, mohan polamar, who is also a yoga teacher. oh the access. 
this is the couple who runs the practice room @thepracticeroomdotin in wheeler road, bangalore. 
the women whom he harassed got together and created this comic.

when the women complained, the practice room put together a committee. this included the harasser's wife who also runs the place along with the harasser. 
there was flat out denial, gaslighting and aggression.  the women were told the complaint would be entertained only if there were more than 10 women who complained. when the women insisted, he was asked to take time off. but a month later he's back to teaching, having "reflected deeply." and then, the cleverest cut of all. the husband and wife duo have coopted this comic to circulate this among their classes claiming what a great illustration of how not to behave as a yoga teacher.

#metooindia
#metoo

u.s. militia groups head to border, stirred by trump‚Äôs call to arms .
.
falfurrias, tex. ‚Äîgun-carrying civilian groups and border vigilantes have heard a call to arms in president trump‚Äôs warnings about threats to american security posed by caravans of central american migrants moving through mexico. they‚Äôre packing coolers and tents, oiling rifles and tuning up aerial drones, with plans to form caravans of their own and trail american troops to the border. ‚Äúwe‚Äôll observe and report, and offer aid in any way we can,‚Äù said shannon mcgauley, a bail bondsman in the dallas suburbs who is president of the texas minutemen. mcgauley said he was preparing to head for the rio grande in coming days. ‚Äúwe‚Äôve proved ourselves before, and we‚Äôll prove ourselves again,‚Äù he said. .
.
mcgauley and others have been roused by the president‚Äôs call to restore order and defend the country against what trump has called ‚Äúan invasion,‚Äù as thousands of central american migrants advance slowly through southern mexico toward the u.s. border. trump has insisted that ‚Äúunknown middle easterners,‚Äù ‚Äúvery tough fighters,‚Äù and large numbers of violent criminals are traveling among the women, children and families heading north on foot.

the texas minutemen, according to mcgauley, have 100 volunteers en route to the rio grande who want to help stop the migrants, with more likely on the way.

text:
mercury 13

autumn morning and i‚Äôm making apple pie
listening to cerys‚Äô soothing voice through the radio, my sunday ally.
talking about shamhain and traditions of the past
smelling the apples and cinnamon in bliss, at last.

now that the veils are thin and kali tends to whisper to my heart
now i can see that life and death are not that far apart
inanna takes me by the hand, shows me the apples on the plant
and the darkness below the land
and it‚Äôs ok
it is how it‚Äôs always been.

at this point comes sue to talk about wally and her race for space
the story unfolds of 13 women who never made it to the stars‚Äô arms
they gave up so much but they didn‚Äôt get there cause it was the 50s
shots of grease flash by, thinking we were so liberated at the end of the 70s.
it was ok for an older man to put an aspirin in a girls coke back then
the dreams with which we grew up are so fraud by men.
yet wally hasn‚Äôt stopped dreaming 
and plans to go with the wings of the virgin.

13 the number of the sisterhood burned in fires
13 the number of transition and changes
13 the place where we can see inbetween the two worlds
feared for centuries, 13 is here to stay!
as you‚Äôre pulled from trump to #metoo
13 is where you‚Äôre at!

and i‚Äôm fuming with anger
grating these apples to their core
why am i asked why i‚Äôm not wearing makeup or a skirt in 2018?!
what is it that i need to prove to be free to live in safety and respect?
if wally flies to the arms of the stars will we still be in 13?

i‚Äôm still making apple pie like a housewife in the 50s
and wally has the virgin‚Äôs ticket to the stars, hoping to fly in her 80s
in times of shamhain i‚Äôm dreaming of change, honoring what has come before me, hoping to re-arrange. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî #mercury13 #autumn #applepie #cerysmatthewsshow #shamhain #apple #kali #inanna #goddess #13 #wallyfunksraceforspace #sisterhood #hope#change

text:
seasons passed by consuming her. and she loved being consumed. like there was no other world. like this season will last forever even though she knew it wouldn't. and she had loved all of them with fervour, each one for different reasons. summer for the mouth watering fruits, monsoon for the thunders, autumn for how sweet the winds felt against her skin,winters for the frozen lakes. though passing away of one season made her sad, but she did look forward to the next season and it's many vibrant gifts. a change, a new intoxication, a new world, new experiences. and then the spring came. daffodils, lily , tulips. the many colors of this season overwhelmed her. before she could gather herself, the celebration and the festivity in the air enthralled her very soul. the earth gladly received the embraces of the sun. she couldn't describe the fragrance of the breath of spring in words! life was alive in everything! but spring was short-lived. and she ached for it even as it was passing away. she wasn't looking forward to the fruits of summer, as she held onto a wilting lily.  spring didn't live with her, but lived in her forever. 
he was the spring of her life üíñ
.
.
.

text:
when walking around bratislava i just kept seeing people spot around a dirty street sign and final (as i can be a bit slow) i looked down to the man at work statue. i have never seen anything like it. when on a tour i even learnt that some believe he is meant to be smiling as he is looking up dresses - not her #metoo era. it is also had it own street sign saying man at work as cars wouldn't see it and hit it. i like the concept of this piece of art but the expression on the man himself for me is a little creepy. nevertheless appreciate it for representing the working culture of slovakia. ‚ú®

text:
...continued from post 1 of 2.

but i digress. i don't feel brave. i just feel incredibly loved and supported. and sometimes that is what it takes to be able to stand up and speak one's truth. sometimes that is all it takes to be brave.

if you are going through something and are looking for external support before you commit to your next step, i encourage you to take the leap and commit 100% to what is right for you anyway.  energy has a magical way of seeking like to like and if you project strength (even it starts out as an attempt to convince yourself you can do this) you will attract strength and support from even the most unexpected of sources. sometimes, the universe waits for you to commit 100% to your well-being before it sends you guidance. so make that route map and begin with baby steps. there are no gallant rescues in real life and there is never a better time than now.

if you know someone going through something in life, i encourage you to be mindful of your words. to refrain from judgement, mindless commentary and sympathy. just be kind. knowingly or unknowingly, we are all creating an environment that can either heal or hurt the ones around us. let us be that village that heals. let us be someone's source of strength today.

love,
atikaa
.

text:
even if you don't know @jillsoloway's name, then you probably know their work. they're the award-winning creator behind the tv show @transparentamazon. they also won a directing award at @sundanceorg for the rather lovely/confronting film called afternoon delight and have written for and exec produced shows like six feet under and united states of tara. on an entirely different note, if the rumours this week are true, jill is apparently dating the australian comedian @hannah_gadsby of nanette fame (hello, power couple!). this book tracks the journey from when jill's parent came out as trans, inspiring the hit tv show and setting them off on a journey through understanding their privilege, embracing their queerness and discovering their own non-binary identity.

i'm always really interested in stories about people who discover their queerness not in their youth but in middle age or later. their journeys are so interesting. jill was rapidly approaching 50 when their parent came out, setting off the chain of events reshaped their life. i really enjoyed how honest jill was in this book was about some of the decisions they've made along the way that they later realised were probably not the best: casting a man to play a trans woman, writing a tv show about this character with no trans writers or actors in the first season, being at the forefront of the #metoo movement but then finding themselves having a selfish reaction to accusations made towards a man on their own show. more than anything in this book, it is a journey towards jill discovering their own privilege that shapes this story - in addition to divorcing their husband and embarking on relationships with women and transforming their own identity. a really fascinating read; i'm super interested to see what jill will create next.

ruth writes about the many different types of abuse including: gaslighting, psychical abuse, emotional abuse, digital abuse, financial abuse, sexual abuse and coercion. she also discusses making safety plans and covering your tracks.
-
ruth discusses the effect abuse can have on your sense of self, often needed to rebuild your personality and identity. in her words ‚Äúit is complex and terrifying and lonely. having to dedicate time to finding out who you are feels weird and hard‚Äù
-
her honesty is so inspiring. please go and read her words, on her grid and the grlclub blog.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower christopher wiley on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook (fb.o) users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

mark hosenball
reuters
